<p>The usage will probably be similar in that you will want to use <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> to control rotation</p>","post_number":9,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-02-13T20:30:19.957Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":8,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":142,"readers_count":141,"score":38.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":454178,"topic_slug":"coding-for-apriltag-ids-with-a-limelight","display_username":"Jason Daming","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":63914,"username":"SmartKirb99","name":"","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/e495f1/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":18342,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"WPILib Developer (Documentation), CSA"},"post_url":"/t/coding-for-apriltag-ids-with-a-limelight/454178/9","custom_user_title":"WPILib Developer (Documentation), CSA","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3308708,"name":"","username":"SmartKirb99","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/s/e495f1/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-02-13T20:38:15.810Z","cooked":"<p>I believe the robot I am programming also doesn’t have <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span>, I assume that because the robot I’m testing it on has VictorSPX as the motor controllers</p>","post_number":10,"post_type":1,"posts_count":22,"updated_at":"2024-02-13T20:38:15.810Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":9,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":131,"readers_count":130,"score":46.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":454178,"topic_slug":"coding-for-apriltag-ids-with-a-limelight","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":18342,"username":"jdaming","name":"Jason Daming","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/jdaming/{size}/137720_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":63914,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming Co-Captain"},"post_url":"/t/coding-for-apriltag-ids-with-a-limelight/454178/10","custom_user_title":"Programming Co-Captain","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3308724,"name":"","username":"Hollisms","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/hollisms/{size}/110925_2.png","created_at":"2024-02-13T20:54:59.194Z","cooked":"<p>Here is a simple “P” controller…</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto"> public double getRotationalRate() {
    // if we don't see a game piece don't turn
    if (!this.isGamePieceFound()) {
      return 0;
    }

    double answer = 0;
    double offset = -Math.toRadians(m_LL_GamePiece.getEntry("tx").getDouble(0));

    double deadzone = 0.05; // TODO tune this
    double kP = 1.5; // TODO tune this
    double kS = 0.1; // TODO tune this

    if (offset &lt; 0.0) {
      kS = kS * -1;
    }

    answer = (offset * kP) + kS;

    if (Math.abs(offset) &lt; deadzone) {
      answer = 0;
    }

    return answer;
  }
</code></pre>
